I understand the idea you're going for, but to me, it breaks tone entirely to have the containment protocols act as though acceleration and increase in speed are the same. What's actually happening with the object, as far as the scientists are concerned, is that it has a highly highly variable acceleration, ranging from .008m/s2, or more (calculated using a picosecond, since that's the closest to instantaneous they'd probably feel comfortable measuring). There is no such thing as acceleration without being affected by direction, from a physics standpoint. Could the object do that? Certainly, but that's at least as much of an anomaly as the eating people's brains, and should be noted as such in the procedures. As written, someone's going to come up with the same idea as me, and try it, and end up feeding D-Class to the thing because nobody bothered to tell him that the procedures neglected to mention the most important part of the object when it comes to containment.







